00:12:18.179 --> 00:12:20.419
here with the nearest three stations.

00:12:20.419 --> 00:12:23.219
And then we find the station that for a given time of day, in this case, I just picked 12

00:12:23.219 --> 00:12:28.179
p.m. for everything, is most likely to actually have a bike available and where you deposit

00:12:28.179 --> 00:12:31.539
the bike is most likely to have a spot that you can put the bike back.

00:12:31.539 --> 00:12:38.179
The whole point of this is to provide you with the most, let's say, low-stress way of

00:12:38.179 --> 00:12:41.299
planning a date, executing a date, so you can focus on what's important.

00:12:41.299 --> 00:12:44.179
And that is paying attention to your partner and telling them how important they are to

00:12:44.179 --> 00:12:46.500
you, because a computer took care of all the grunt work.

00:12:51.859 --> 00:12:52.739
Thank you, Shashank.

00:12:52.739 --> 00:12:54.419
Judges, do you have any questions?

00:12:54.419 --> 00:12:58.739
So you did all this in only, what, an hour and a half or so?

00:12:58.739 --> 00:13:02.419
But I'm curious, if you had another hour and a half, where else would you see yourself

00:13:02.419 --> 00:13:02.900
taking this?

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:06.820
What I was really looking forward to was having this deployed on a mobile app and just having

00:13:06.820 --> 00:13:07.780
a QR code over here.

00:13:07.780 --> 00:13:09.380
And then you guys went and looked at it yourself.

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:12.900
I don't want to comment on other people's projects, but I think I could get it deployed

00:13:12.900 --> 00:13:15.219
faster than most people could.

00:13:15.219 --> 00:13:20.659
If you were to start again, are there things you wish you knew right when you started that

00:13:20.659 --> 00:13:24.020
would make you develop this differently, sort of explore different things?

00:13:24.020 --> 00:13:26.179
One of the big things that I did is I used Haversine distance.

00:13:26.659 --> 00:13:32.260
So the distance by how the crow flies for the distance between the different bike stations,

00:13:32.260 --> 00:13:33.780
which is not necessarily accurate.

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:36.340
And in such a small distance in a city, it should be fine.

00:13:36.340 --> 00:13:40.419
But I would really like to go to the Google Maps API and actually get a path and then

00:13:41.140 --> 00:13:44.979
use a GeoJSON object to plot it on top of this map.

00:13:44.979 --> 00:13:47.859
So it looks more like a Google Maps native view.

00:13:47.859 --> 00:13:48.659
Thank you, Shashank.

00:13:48.659 --> 00:13:56.739
Judges, what did you think about Shashank's performance?

00:13:56.739 --> 00:13:59.140
I feel like that's going to be hard to beat.

00:13:59.140 --> 00:14:00.979
I mean, that was quite impressive.

00:14:00.979 --> 00:14:04.739
I feel like the things that were the most impressive were it really did demonstrate

00:14:04.739 --> 00:14:06.179
quite a bit of creative thinking.

00:14:06.179 --> 00:14:07.940
I really loved his presentation.

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:09.700
He seemed like he had a story to tell.

00:14:09.700 --> 00:14:11.059
He was confident with it.

00:14:11.059 --> 00:14:12.340
I was really impressed.

00:14:12.340 --> 00:14:14.419
And that's a real strong start.

00:14:14.419 --> 00:14:20.500
I really loved the way in which he used ChatGPT as sort of just a serendipity generator.

00:14:20.500 --> 00:14:24.659
The fact that he could correlate that with the data that exists on this reference set

00:14:24.659 --> 00:14:29.219
and then go search against it and present it in a map means that you get this grounding

00:14:29.219 --> 00:14:32.260
of the results and you get the narrative next to it to sort of support it.

00:14:32.260 --> 00:14:33.859
I thought it was really strong.

00:14:33.859 --> 00:14:34.340
Amazing.

00:14:34.340 --> 00:14:34.979
Thank you, judges.

00:14:34.979 --> 00:14:37.460
We'll bring in the next competitors.

00:14:37.460 --> 00:14:38.020
Welcome back.

00:14:38.020 --> 00:14:41.859
This is Team MMA with Mickey, Monica, and Alex.

00:14:41.859 --> 00:14:42.340
Good luck.

00:14:42.340 --> 00:14:46.099
When we looked at this data set, we were trying to think of something that would differentiate

00:14:46.099 --> 00:14:52.020
us from our competitors who are going to do some boring data analysis, which I mean, come

00:14:52.020 --> 00:14:53.219
on, guys, a dashboard.

00:14:53.219 --> 00:14:54.979
Like, we need something better.

00:14:54.979 --> 00:14:58.500
A user is going to input their address, date, and time.

00:14:58.500 --> 00:15:00.820
This is when they're going to need the bike in the future.

00:15:00.820 --> 00:15:06.900
We're going to take the data that we have and forecast into the future a time when they're

00:15:06.900 --> 00:15:11.059
inputting this information, and we're going to project whether a bike is going to be available

00:15:11.059 --> 00:15:12.979
at that time at the nearest location.

00:15:12.979 --> 00:15:18.500
What it will give as the output or would give as the output is a map with the location of

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:21.059
the nearest station that has an available bike.

00:15:21.059 --> 00:15:24.820
If it does not have an available bike, it would not be part of the output.

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:30.099
It would also give the distance to that station based off of your longitudinal current data.

00:15:30.099 --> 00:15:32.900
And so as you can see, we don't have a map down here.

00:15:35.059 --> 00:15:39.619
We were this close, and in fact, we could have hard-coded it and we could have deceived

00:15:39.619 --> 00:15:42.260
you guys into thinking it was working, but we chose not to do that.

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:46.340
The first way we could approach this was a purely, like, a time series machine learning

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:46.739
problem.

00:15:46.739 --> 00:15:49.780
The problem was essentially granularity in terms of seconds and minutes.

00:15:49.780 --> 00:15:54.179
So then we said, okay, what if we kind of just did essentially like a dummy sort of

00:15:54.179 --> 00:15:54.659
lookup?

00:15:54.659 --> 00:15:56.099
So user inputs an address.

00:15:56.820 --> 00:16:00.659
Using that address, we use a GeoPi package to then get the lat long.

00:16:00.659 --> 00:16:06.500
We would then also, using a Haverstein distance, we would then get the lat long of all the

00:16:06.500 --> 00:16:07.380
different stations.

00:16:07.940 --> 00:16:11.460
And then we essentially say, okay, we then convert it into kilometers.

00:16:11.460 --> 00:16:15.619
And then we say, give us like locations and then we return it.

00:16:15.619 --> 00:16:17.460
And so that is the intent of the code.

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:18.659
Thank you, Team MMA.

00:16:18.659 --> 00:16:20.179
Judges, do you have any questions?

00:16:20.179 --> 00:16:24.020
How long did that last issue that you were facing trying to get that map to render?

00:16:24.020 --> 00:16:25.940
How long were you working on that?

00:16:25.940 --> 00:16:33.140
We actually divvied up some of the tasks so that we can work on things at the same time.

00:16:33.140 --> 00:16:36.419
I think that lasted about 45 minutes.

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:43.380
The difficulty we had was understanding when do we switch from like vanilla Python to like

00:16:43.380 --> 00:16:45.940
essentially Jupyter, like Python, which is what we're using.

00:16:45.940 --> 00:16:52.260
And then how do we then make that final translation into shiny Python with like widgets?

00:16:52.260 --> 00:16:57.700
And then that was actually really where we got stuck was essentially like the input text

00:16:57.700 --> 00:17:02.419
for the fields and then just returning the values and making sure it would like flow

00:17:02.419 --> 00:17:03.859
through the rest of like the logic.

00:17:03.859 --> 00:17:05.219
Thank you so much, Team MMA.

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:06.579
Really appreciate it.

00:17:07.939 --> 00:17:08.979
Now, are we allowed to stay?

00:17:10.579 --> 00:17:12.180
Judges, what did you think?

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:14.099
It is, you know, it's such a heartbreak.

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:17.540
Such a heartbreak, especially when they felt like they were close.

00:17:17.540 --> 00:17:22.020
They did not really start with the existing app and kind of minorly change it.

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:23.859
They seemed like they were starting from scratch.

00:17:23.859 --> 00:17:25.300
So that is quite ambitious.

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:26.819
And I like to see that.

00:17:26.819 --> 00:17:31.540
I really like the fact that they went big for the thing that they built, which is if

00:17:31.540 --> 00:17:35.380
that existed, you could, you know, package it up and ship as like an app for people that

00:17:35.380 --> 00:17:36.900
would want to use.

00:17:36.900 --> 00:17:40.339
So more than just a demo of the technology, like that was a real thing that they just

00:17:40.339 --> 00:17:41.939
said, this is what we're going to try to do.

00:17:41.939 --> 00:17:47.459
If all that was taking the better part of three hours, then it was not realistic to

00:17:48.099 --> 00:17:50.099
expect integration to take about 15 minutes.

00:17:50.099 --> 00:17:55.300
It's a strong contrast to, you know, some of the other competitors who kind of knew

00:17:55.300 --> 00:18:00.579
coming in exactly what their strengths were and then like add one new thing to it as opposed

00:18:00.579 --> 00:18:03.699
to, you know, doing a lot of things that were a little bit of a stretch.

00:18:03.699 --> 00:18:04.579
Real bummer, though.

00:18:04.579 --> 00:18:07.300
I was really hoping to see that come together.

00:18:07.300 --> 00:18:07.699
Amazing.

00:18:07.699 --> 00:18:08.739
Thank you, judges.

00:18:08.739 --> 00:18:10.260
We will bring in the next team.

00:18:10.260 --> 00:18:14.900
Team Jack of Jack, Keith and Avery.

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:15.459
Welcome.

00:18:15.459 --> 00:18:18.180
It's now your time to present in front of the judges.

00:18:18.180 --> 00:18:20.900
Who here has seen bike shares?

00:18:20.900 --> 00:18:23.619
Who's seen like delivery trucks of bikes being dumped?

00:18:24.500 --> 00:18:25.699
We can all understand why, right?

00:18:25.699 --> 00:18:27.300
Because the system doesn't work perfectly.

00:18:27.300 --> 00:18:31.380
It's not perfect cycles where you have a network of nodes and you have bikes going

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:33.140
to and from various nodes.

00:18:33.140 --> 00:18:38.339
So the problem that we're solving for essentially is that there is an overflow of bikes going

00:18:38.339 --> 00:18:39.699
toward any one given node.

00:18:39.699 --> 00:18:40.739
So I grew up in Chicago.

00:18:40.739 --> 00:18:41.699
I lived in Chicago.

00:18:41.699 --> 00:18:45.459
And the biggest problem is that everyone either goes to the loop or comes from the loop.

00:18:45.459 --> 00:18:49.459
And then there's always an issue with bikes being dumped somewhere.

00:18:49.459 --> 00:18:54.020
What we're trying to solve for is how do we know at any given time, what is the capacity

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:56.420
at this node, at this station?

00:18:56.420 --> 00:19:00.260
If we can know at any given time, what the capacity is, how it's changing, then we can

00:19:00.260 --> 00:19:02.180
react and we can send these bikes to and from nodes.

00:19:02.180 --> 00:19:03.459
So that's the problem that we're solving.

00:19:03.459 --> 00:19:08.420
The way we chose to look at this was with a geo scatter.

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:10.739
I love geo scatters because it lets you see a lot of detail.

00:19:10.739 --> 00:19:12.819
You could zoom in, zoom out of detail.

00:19:12.819 --> 00:19:18.739
And so we actually ended up creating is an interactive geo plot here that basically shows

00:19:18.739 --> 00:19:23.219
you throughout time for all three cities, what the capacity is.

00:19:23.219 --> 00:19:28.020
So we basically took all the stations and figured out how many bikes can each station

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:33.140
hold at any given point in time, on average, how many bikes are available.

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:36.739
And so Keith, if you want to press play, we have from midnight to basically midnight

00:19:37.540 --> 00:19:38.579
throughout the day.

00:19:39.459 --> 00:19:41.780
And it's going one step at a time.

00:19:41.780 --> 00:19:44.099
And these dots are changing based off of that.

00:19:44.099 --> 00:19:48.500
With the dashboard that we created, we actually have the ability to show you guys the capacity

00:19:48.500 --> 00:19:49.780
from zero to one.

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:54.420
We can show you which ones are dangerously low and need someone to like a truck to be

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:56.420
sent over there at any point in the day.

00:19:56.420 --> 00:20:00.500
And we can also show you how many bikes are available at any of those points throughout

00:20:00.500 --> 00:20:00.979
the day.

00:20:00.979 --> 00:20:07.300
Hey everyone, I'm on the experimental research group at the BikeShare dashboard company.

00:20:07.939 --> 00:20:09.380
And Avery here is a new dad.

00:20:09.939 --> 00:20:16.420
He doesn't always have his hands available to look at dashboards of bike availability.

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:20.339
We have this new feature we've incorporated into our app.

00:20:20.339 --> 00:20:28.020
And if I start yelling and being really loud, then we will see shortly that, as you can

00:20:28.020 --> 00:20:31.859
tell right now, you're really zoomed in and getting proper coordinates.

00:20:31.859 --> 00:20:37.619
So in two hours, what we were able to do, if we can get this to work, is we can take

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:43.219
volume or audio as input and we can use it to control the visual.

00:20:43.699 --> 00:20:44.199
Ta-da!

00:20:44.819 --> 00:20:45.780
Thank you for watching.

00:20:49.780 --> 00:20:51.459
How did this all come together?

00:20:51.459 --> 00:20:56.260
Was this like sort of the original plan or was this something that, you know, there's

00:20:56.260 --> 00:21:00.500
a bunch of just experimenting and then it sort of came together at the last minute?

00:21:00.500 --> 00:21:01.699
This was our original plan.

00:21:01.699 --> 00:21:04.420
We always had Keith in that department, that special Keith department.

00:21:04.420 --> 00:21:06.020
So he was always working on that.

00:21:06.020 --> 00:21:09.140
And then Jack and I, I really like to see things visually.

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:12.500
Like, how do you visually see what 190,000 rows looks like?

00:21:12.579 --> 00:21:16.979
And so, and I love with animation too, because I can like tell a lot of, a lot of stories

00:21:16.979 --> 00:21:17.859
in one individual things.

00:21:17.859 --> 00:21:22.180
But what I realized is there's like five stations in most cities where there's like 50 bikes

00:21:22.180 --> 00:21:24.260
and the rest of the station is usually in about four bikes.

00:21:24.260 --> 00:21:27.459
So when you're looking at bike availability, it's always going to be skewed pretty heavily.

00:21:27.459 --> 00:21:29.540
So learned some pretty cool patterns from the day.

00:21:29.540 --> 00:21:36.099
I think what was challenging was trying to balance the stuff that was given versus how

00:21:36.099 --> 00:21:38.339
I normally approach data analysis.

00:21:38.339 --> 00:21:42.900
I'm building off the work of others, not inspecting for the first time, while also

00:21:42.900 --> 00:21:47.540
trying out a new library in terms of visualization.

00:21:47.540 --> 00:21:53.459
So it's sort of like there was like two to three axes of newness, which I underestimated

00:21:53.459 --> 00:21:57.859
the challenge that that has, especially given time constraints and given a team working

00:21:57.859 --> 00:21:58.579
together.

00:21:58.579 --> 00:21:59.459
Thank you, Team Jack.

00:22:02.500 --> 00:22:05.380
Judges, what did you think about Team Jack?

00:22:05.380 --> 00:22:09.300
They had that problem with the animation with Plotly and they sort of bailed and had

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:11.380
it like just load separately.

00:22:11.380 --> 00:22:14.979
But I liked that they did that and didn't just sort of can the feature, you know, like

00:22:14.979 --> 00:22:19.939
recognizing that there was something of value created here, even if it was not exactly in

00:22:19.939 --> 00:22:21.699
the way that they intended it to be.

00:22:21.699 --> 00:22:27.939
I think it's pretty interesting that their instinct was trying to show an animation in

00:22:27.939 --> 00:22:33.380
an interactive app, but I thought it was worthwhile for them to engage in that.

00:22:33.380 --> 00:22:37.380
And sure, it would have been great to see that working.

00:22:37.380 --> 00:22:40.979
The most actionable sort of like vision of the ones we've seen so far.

00:22:40.979 --> 00:22:44.339
I really like, again, the fact that sort of folks thinking on their feet and say, OK,

00:22:44.339 --> 00:22:48.739
we can show what we meant by this on a separate place and so that you can see what we were

00:22:48.739 --> 00:22:49.300
trying to go.

00:22:49.300 --> 00:22:50.579
And I really appreciate that.

00:22:50.579 --> 00:22:51.060
Amazing.

00:22:51.060 --> 00:22:51.699
Thank you, judges.

00:22:51.699 --> 00:22:53.140
We'll send in the next team.

00:22:53.140 --> 00:22:56.819
Team Positively Skewed, it is now your time to impress the judges.

00:22:56.819 --> 00:23:00.900
There's actually not much to show, but I think it's a fantastic retrospective.

00:23:00.900 --> 00:23:05.380
Instead of creating a business user focused app, we wanted to create something for an

00:23:05.380 --> 00:23:06.819
actual customer to use.

00:23:06.819 --> 00:23:11.140
So when we when we analyze the data, we probably spent a little too much time trying to figure

00:23:11.140 --> 00:23:15.380
out what some of the columns meant, which is really great in the workplace, but probably

00:23:15.380 --> 00:23:16.739
not as good for a hackathon.

00:23:16.739 --> 00:23:21.619
And then we eventually settled on a plan of of creating basically a button that simulates

00:23:21.619 --> 00:23:22.099
a person.

00:23:22.739 --> 00:23:25.380
So we would take the by city.

00:23:25.380 --> 00:23:31.459
We would take the min max lat long and the min max time and then simulate a person being

00:23:31.459 --> 00:23:35.380
in one of these cities during that time period of the data, which is about four days.

00:23:35.380 --> 00:23:41.380
Then we would basically find the closest stations which had an available dock, the top three

00:23:41.380 --> 00:23:42.660
and the closest with a bike.

00:23:42.660 --> 00:23:46.260
So for returning and forgetting, probably the biggest challenge would have been doing

00:23:46.260 --> 00:23:51.699
actual GPS distances versus just have a sign like linear distances.

00:23:51.699 --> 00:23:55.780
However, the only the only thing we got to was actually calculating those numbers.

00:23:55.780 --> 00:23:59.939
So we got like random timestamp and lat long generation by city.

00:23:59.939 --> 00:24:02.420
So if you click it, it continues to generate them.

00:24:02.420 --> 00:24:04.819
And we just printed it just to show that we did all this stuff.

00:24:04.819 --> 00:24:09.060
I was working on the front end bit and then Harpreet was working on a lot of these helper

00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:09.939
functions.

00:24:09.939 --> 00:24:11.619
That was actually a really effective workflow.

00:24:11.619 --> 00:24:12.420
Just not enough time.

00:24:15.459 --> 00:24:16.260
So proud of it.

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:17.219
It was still lots of fun.

00:24:19.300 --> 00:24:21.219
Judges, do you have any questions?

00:24:21.219 --> 00:24:27.060
Yeah, I'm curious how much how much time had you planned to give yourself to implement

00:24:27.060 --> 00:24:30.020
the sort of interactive UI portions of it?

00:24:30.020 --> 00:24:34.979
We didn't actually try to allocate specific blocks of time to doing the different steps.

00:24:34.979 --> 00:24:39.300
We tried to do each step essentially as fast as we thought should be done.

00:24:39.300 --> 00:24:43.140
It's something I'm very used to in what I do and in my background.

00:24:43.140 --> 00:24:46.819
And I guess like a hackathon requires a different kind of like approach.

00:24:46.819 --> 00:24:52.020
I think we spent like literally 80% of the time checking on the data and thinking that

00:24:52.020 --> 00:24:54.099
the 20% would be super easy.

00:24:54.099 --> 00:24:57.140
But when the time came, it was like, oh, no, that 20% is not enough.

00:24:57.140 --> 00:24:58.260
Thank you so much, team.

00:24:58.260 --> 00:25:00.739
It was positively interesting.

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:06.020
Thank you, guys.

00:25:06.020 --> 00:25:08.500
Judges, what did you think of that team?

00:25:08.500 --> 00:25:13.140
It was great to see when that reactive thing came back that they like hooked up the button

00:25:13.219 --> 00:25:16.739
to doing something and that they were able to get that kind of like reactive loop.

00:25:16.739 --> 00:25:17.859
That was really good to see.

00:25:17.859 --> 00:25:20.660
This team maybe struggled with time management a little bit.

00:25:20.660 --> 00:25:26.819
The process is as interesting as the output and seeing how people approach these challenges.

00:25:26.819 --> 00:25:31.540
And for this group, you can tell like they're seasoned professionals and they know that

00:25:31.540 --> 00:25:33.859
you need to watch out for pitfalls in the data.

00:25:33.859 --> 00:25:37.380
It is a shame to sort of see folks having a plan and like all of this code written and

00:25:37.380 --> 00:25:41.699
then at the end of the day, you hit the deadline and you don't get to see the benefits of that.

00:25:41.699 --> 00:25:44.739
Avoiding that from happening, I think it's sort of like a good way to think about your

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:48.579
future like hackathon participation.

00:25:48.579 --> 00:25:48.979
Amazing.

00:25:48.979 --> 00:25:49.780
Thank you, judges.

00:25:49.780 --> 00:25:52.099
We will send in now the final group.

00:25:52.099 --> 00:25:53.939
We welcome Null Consulting.

00:25:53.939 --> 00:25:55.780
It's now your time to impress the judges.

00:25:55.780 --> 00:25:56.739
We're Null Consulting.

00:25:56.739 --> 00:26:00.500
We're working for bikesarefun.com given the data we have.

00:26:00.500 --> 00:26:01.540
This is their lovely logo.

00:26:01.540 --> 00:26:02.660
It's very professional.

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:04.420
This is made with Quarto in spirit.

00:26:04.420 --> 00:26:05.459
Bike sharing is hard.

00:26:05.459 --> 00:26:09.699
You can see all these horror stories, but we think this is an opportunity.

00:26:09.699 --> 00:26:13.380
The problem, low-use areas isn't a sign of poor performance.

00:26:14.099 --> 00:26:17.219
Instead, there are opportunities to increase revenue.

00:26:17.219 --> 00:26:18.020
But how?

00:26:18.020 --> 00:26:20.180
We did extensive research with Userbase.

00:26:20.739 --> 00:26:21.380
It was Julie.

00:26:22.260 --> 00:26:23.859
We found out the following.

00:26:23.859 --> 00:26:27.300
Users often use the bikes not for commuting, but for leisure activities.

00:26:27.300 --> 00:26:29.219
This was especially true when they're traveling.

00:26:29.219 --> 00:26:31.859
Bike services are seen as an amazing way to explore the city.

00:26:31.859 --> 00:26:37.300
So the solution, rather than ignoring low-use areas, we instead need to encourage users

00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:39.300
why it's worth visiting these areas.

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:42.260
So welcome to Bikes Are Fun City Guides.

00:26:42.260 --> 00:26:45.699
By tying restaurant entertainment data with low-use stations,

00:26:45.699 --> 00:26:48.979
we can unlock a completely different market and grow your business.

00:26:48.979 --> 00:26:52.180
Well, we used a model to essentially find the low-use areas.

00:26:52.180 --> 00:26:57.619
We used interquartile range to essentially figure out which ones we could focus on.

00:26:57.619 --> 00:26:59.619
In each of these sections, there's about, I don't know,

00:26:59.619 --> 00:27:02.099
somewhere 30 possible areas that we noticed.

00:27:02.099 --> 00:27:03.619
And we decided to make sure they were mapped out.

00:27:03.619 --> 00:27:06.500
And basically, the next phase of this project is to start

00:27:07.300 --> 00:27:11.380
scraping the internet for different areas, different lats and longitudes,

00:27:11.380 --> 00:27:15.540
that have interesting spaces that we could then start pushing to your guys' app

00:27:15.540 --> 00:27:21.939
to encourage your users to go to those spaces that could then increase travel and use of these bikes.

00:27:21.939 --> 00:27:25.300
I kind of like to think about it like a Michelin guide, but for bikes.

00:27:25.300 --> 00:27:28.739
We weren't able to do that last step, but we started scraping data from

00:27:28.739 --> 00:27:32.979
Michelin and TripAdvisor for top points of interest, restaurants,

00:27:32.979 --> 00:27:37.459
to fit in with this theme of routing people to stations near restaurants

00:27:38.420 --> 00:27:40.900
and using that restaurant data to just guide people

00:27:40.900 --> 00:27:44.020
and help them explore the city while also using bikes for fun.

00:27:44.020 --> 00:27:44.579
Any questions?

00:27:48.579 --> 00:27:52.900
I'm thinking more about you trying to use a model-based or a stats-based

00:27:53.459 --> 00:27:56.260
way to find the things you were interested in.

00:27:56.260 --> 00:28:00.900
How was the process of thinking about that within the reactive framework?

00:28:00.900 --> 00:28:05.140
I had originally separated the stations and bikes data separately.

00:28:05.140 --> 00:28:09.140
And then there was an issue where it was trying to calculate something that I was expecting from

00:28:09.859 --> 00:28:12.739
one of the other calculations that was basically going to run all the time.

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:17.300
And so then I was like, oh, this is not there yet because they're constantly rerunning.

00:28:17.300 --> 00:28:19.219
So that was one of those things that I was like, what's happening?

00:28:19.219 --> 00:28:20.579
And then I kind of figured that out.

00:28:20.579 --> 00:28:25.219
If you were to start over, where would you do things differently and how?

00:28:26.099 --> 00:28:27.459
What are the lessons you've learned?

00:28:27.459 --> 00:28:29.459
Exploring the data, that's where we start it.

00:28:29.459 --> 00:28:32.420
And you can get lost in that, especially for a hackathon because it's so fun.

00:28:32.420 --> 00:28:34.979
Good data people should start with data exploration,

00:28:34.979 --> 00:28:37.219
but within the confines of a hackathon,

00:28:37.219 --> 00:28:39.699
maybe two of us could have started with data exploration

00:28:39.699 --> 00:28:43.140
and one of us could have started with sample Cordo dashboards

00:28:43.140 --> 00:28:45.780
and starting to understand that a little bit better.

00:28:45.780 --> 00:28:47.300
So we kind of saved that part for the end

00:28:47.300 --> 00:28:49.859
because we first wanted to know what data we were looking at.

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:52.500
And that had us rushing towards the end.

00:28:52.500 --> 00:28:56.099
We could have split the work a little bit better and had one person focus on Cordo.

00:28:56.099 --> 00:28:58.020
Thank you so much, Null Consulting.

00:28:58.660 --> 00:28:59.699
You may now exit.

00:29:04.339 --> 00:29:07.780
Judges, what did you think of Team Null Consulting?

00:29:08.500 --> 00:29:11.780
I really liked their, I guess, the sort of product side.

00:29:11.780 --> 00:29:12.979
The humor was great.

00:29:12.979 --> 00:29:15.060
The user research was hilarious.

00:29:15.060 --> 00:29:17.699
I mean, not just hilarious, but also like that is what you would do.

00:29:17.699 --> 00:29:19.300
You know, if you were looking into this,

00:29:19.300 --> 00:29:22.579
I thought it was really fun from that perspective.

00:29:22.819 --> 00:29:27.140
I'm probably going to give this team my highest presentation style points

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:32.099
because I feel like the way that they presented their work was funny, fun,

00:29:32.660 --> 00:29:35.619
but I think also really demonstrates an understanding

00:29:35.619 --> 00:29:38.020
of what it is like to build data products with people.

00:29:38.020 --> 00:29:42.099
This is the dashboard that you will see in a company somewhere, right?

00:29:42.099 --> 00:29:44.660
Somewhere someone will make the dashboard that has

00:29:44.660 --> 00:29:48.979
a functional basic visualization that has an actual model behind it

00:29:48.979 --> 00:29:51.859
that from there you can guess what is going to happen next, right?

00:29:51.859 --> 00:29:52.979
So is it station by station?

00:29:52.979 --> 00:29:53.540
Is it region?

00:29:53.540 --> 00:29:54.660
How do you like aggregate it?

00:29:54.660 --> 00:29:55.699
What do you do from there?

00:29:55.699 --> 00:29:58.579
Indicative of what you do like in a real world.

00:29:58.579 --> 00:30:00.660
So judges, what are your final thoughts?

00:30:00.660 --> 00:30:03.540
I have to admit, I've got a real soft spot for Team Jack.

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:07.300
You know, I love in hackathons when someone takes the moonshot.

00:30:07.300 --> 00:30:09.140
The problem we solved was real.

00:30:09.140 --> 00:30:11.219
I thought our vision was genuine.

00:30:11.219 --> 00:30:14.420
And that microphone thing, I mean,

00:30:14.420 --> 00:30:17.140
we were surprised that they even attempted something like that.

00:30:17.140 --> 00:30:19.300
If I start yelling and being really loud.

00:30:19.300 --> 00:30:22.099
Ultimately, like it didn't quite work in the demo,

00:30:22.099 --> 00:30:24.420
but I do believe them that it was working an hour ago.

00:30:24.420 --> 00:30:27.060
And I mean, that would have been easily the most impressive

00:30:27.060 --> 00:30:28.739
single feature that we saw all day.

00:30:28.739 --> 00:30:31.380
The fact that it didn't work was a minor technical glitch.

00:30:31.380 --> 00:30:34.819
I do find the work that Null Consulting did so compelling.

00:30:34.819 --> 00:30:38.979
I mean, part of it is the humor and the presentation.

00:30:38.979 --> 00:30:44.660
But what underlies that, like what made it land in terms of the humor,

00:30:44.660 --> 00:30:46.339
it was a substance behind it.

00:30:46.339 --> 00:30:47.619
The competition was fierce,

00:30:47.619 --> 00:30:49.780
but you know, we trained for this every single day

00:30:49.780 --> 00:30:51.140
and came down to execute.

00:30:51.140 --> 00:30:51.780
We did it.

00:30:51.780 --> 00:30:55.540
I really liked that Shashank pulled sort of data from ChatGPT

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:57.939
and then cross-searched it with like the Geo database

00:30:57.939 --> 00:30:59.300
and then showed the results.

00:30:59.300 --> 00:31:01.859
I presented something that I think is genuinely useful.

00:31:02.819 --> 00:31:03.939
And that's all I can ask for myself.

00:31:03.939 --> 00:31:06.099
I thought that was a really interesting demo.

00:31:06.099 --> 00:31:07.780
And then to have it end with like,

00:31:07.780 --> 00:31:09.619
and you reload it and you get a new date.

00:31:09.619 --> 00:31:12.180
I thought it was a sort of nice bit of showmanship.

00:31:12.180 --> 00:31:14.260
So I was a fan of that.

00:31:14.260 --> 00:31:15.459
Presentation went well.

00:31:15.459 --> 00:31:17.219
Unfortunately, we had an unfinished app.

00:31:17.380 --> 00:31:18.900
Our presentation was awesome.

00:31:18.900 --> 00:31:20.500
We worked extremely hard

00:31:20.500 --> 00:31:22.180
and I'm really proud of where we got.

00:31:22.180 --> 00:31:25.060
In the end, we were really close.

00:31:25.060 --> 00:31:27.140
Judges, do you have your final decision?

00:31:28.420 --> 00:31:29.219
I think we know.

00:31:30.339 --> 00:31:31.300
Yeah, I think we know.

00:31:31.300 --> 00:31:32.260
I think we do.

00:31:32.260 --> 00:31:34.979
We are going to announce the winner of the

00:31:34.979 --> 00:31:37.780
So You Think You Can Analyze competition.

00:31:37.780 --> 00:31:38.500
We learned a lot.

00:31:38.500 --> 00:31:39.540
There was a lot of struggle.

00:31:39.540 --> 00:31:40.900
There were some tears,

00:31:40.900 --> 00:31:43.380
but there was also a lot of smiles and a lot of fun.

00:31:43.380 --> 00:31:46.020
We will leave it to the judges to tell you first

00:31:46.099 --> 00:31:49.300
who the runner-up was and then who the final winner was.

00:31:49.300 --> 00:31:52.099
The team that we identified as the runner-up

00:31:52.099 --> 00:31:55.459
is a team who we were impressed with their humor,

00:31:55.459 --> 00:31:57.939
their practical thinking.

00:31:57.939 --> 00:32:00.420
Honestly, how well we think what they did

00:32:00.420 --> 00:32:03.699
would have landed in a real business environment.

00:32:03.699 --> 00:32:05.380
Not doing everything they planned,

00:32:05.380 --> 00:32:08.020
but really showing iterative, complete work.

00:32:08.020 --> 00:32:10.579
Our runner-up is Null Consulting.

00:32:12.339 --> 00:32:13.619
Where's the rest of your team?

00:32:13.619 --> 00:32:16.020
I did the least work on the team,

00:32:16.020 --> 00:32:18.339
but because my team members are not here,

00:32:18.339 --> 00:32:19.619
I'll take all the credit.

00:32:19.619 --> 00:32:20.339
So thank you.

00:32:20.339 --> 00:32:21.140
Thank you.

00:32:21.140 --> 00:32:21.640
Thank you.

00:32:23.140 --> 00:32:23.939
Congratulations.

00:32:24.660 --> 00:32:26.180
And the winner's app.

00:32:26.180 --> 00:32:27.699
And by the way, it was pretty close.

00:32:27.699 --> 00:32:28.339
Pretty close.

00:32:28.339 --> 00:32:29.459
We had to check the math.

00:32:30.020 --> 00:32:31.939
The winner's app had a little bit of everything.

00:32:31.939 --> 00:32:35.619
It had humor, it had grace, it had a clever story.

00:32:35.619 --> 00:32:37.300
There was a little bit of love.

00:32:37.300 --> 00:32:42.819
And this team made it look relatively easy.

00:32:42.900 --> 00:32:46.660
Operating under some serious constraints and disadvantages,

00:32:46.660 --> 00:32:50.020
and yet pulled off a really graceful app

00:32:50.020 --> 00:32:51.540
and a graceful presentation.

00:32:51.540 --> 00:32:53.300
The winner is Team Shashank.

00:33:02.579 --> 00:33:04.900
I had a great time doing this at the end of the day.

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:07.859
I have, I don't know if anyone watches football here,

00:33:07.859 --> 00:33:08.900
but Bill Belichick, right?

00:33:08.900 --> 00:33:11.459
This is, you know, this saying, trust the process, right?

00:33:12.180 --> 00:33:13.619
I think what I've learned is that,

00:33:13.619 --> 00:33:14.900
make a good process to do things

00:33:15.459 --> 00:33:17.380
and don't worry too much about the results.

00:33:17.380 --> 00:33:19.219
And if you keep doing it, you keep iterating on it,

00:33:19.219 --> 00:33:20.819
then you'll eventually, you'll get somewhere

00:33:20.819 --> 00:33:22.500
where at least you're happy with the work you put in, you know?

00:33:22.500 --> 00:33:24.180
My girlfriend does not care about software engineering,

00:33:24.180 --> 00:33:26.180
but she did tell me I'm not romantic enough.

00:33:26.180 --> 00:33:28.420
And so I'm like, okay, how can I offload the,

00:33:28.420 --> 00:33:30.500
how can I offload the work of being romantic to a computer?

00:33:32.020 --> 00:33:33.140
And I think I successfully did it.

00:33:33.140 --> 00:33:33.780
I showed it to her and she's like,

00:33:33.780 --> 00:33:34.660
wait, this is actually pretty good.

00:33:34.660 --> 00:33:36.979
So, you know, there you go.

00:33:38.260 --> 00:33:38.760
There you go.

00:33:41.459 --> 00:33:41.959
Nice.

00:33:43.219 --> 00:33:43.780
There you go.

00:33:43.780 --> 00:33:46.020
You're a former Iron Analyst champion.

00:33:46.020 --> 00:33:49.219
Now you're a So You Think You Can Analyze champion.

00:33:49.219 --> 00:33:52.180
Will anyone ever dethrone Shashank?

00:33:52.180 --> 00:33:53.219
All right, thanks everyone.

00:33:53.219 --> 00:33:54.180
That was amazing.

00:33:54.180 --> 00:33:54.979
Appreciate it.

00:33:58.900 --> 00:34:00.979
Oh my gosh, he's still here.

00:34:00.979 --> 00:34:01.619
Go home.

00:34:02.979 --> 00:34:04.660
It's working now.

00:34:04.660 --> 00:34:06.180
Are you kidding me?

00:34:06.180 --> 00:34:08.820
If I'm loud, if I'm screaming at the damn thing,

00:34:09.379 --> 00:34:10.580
it's zooming in.

00:34:10.580 --> 00:34:12.500
I swear it works, I swear.

00:34:13.379 --> 00:34:14.260
It's working.

00:34:15.860 --> 00:34:16.899
I swear it works.

